			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				Yes, things were great for the larger guilds who are on early enough to raid whoever and whatever they want at whim. <br>  <br> As for guild unity, would you rather have people bickering and arguing for eternity? <br>  <br> Yes, let's keep it to where the smaller guilds or people who can't be on early never get to slay a dragon or raid a plane.  Kinda pointless to play beyond that point for many.  Forget about any form of making the server a community, let's just keep it a competition where people get screwed as normal. <br>  <br> As somebody else pointed out, what happens when our population rises to the 1800's?  WIll you still be completely happy with things remaining as they are now when you find somebody else beating you to everything you plan to hunt?  What about when some larger guild decides they don't care what your plans are, and as your friends log in to raid the dragon or plane you were planning on taking down you have to inform them all to scrap the plans?  Will you still feel this way? <br>  <br> Try to put yourself in the other person's place for a moment, and look at it from the opposite side. <br>  <br> The proposition I make here is a form of compromise, where all guilds can have their opinion heard and compromises over various issues can be met.  It's not imposing some set of rules one person or one group from a certain server developed.  It's not looking at the world and saying &quot;this is how we did it on our server, so that's how it will be here&quot;.  It's a chance for all guilds to be heard, be they large or small, and some form of compromise be had. <br>  <br> I do have an honest question for many people who have argued on this subject: What is it about change that scares you so much?  and if change is apparently not good for you, why did you move servers? <br>  <br> This post was not meant as a flame, so please do not take it as such.		

			</td>
